> (2) Is it possible to view and manipulate protected files in the Unix file 
>     system without owning them (and without being the super-user)?

Sure. Boot as single user, listen on the ethernet for NFS packets, look
at a backup/dump tape, or read from the raw disk device.

> (3) Is it possible to spy on a user's terminal session (to see everything
>     that they see and type)?  How? 

I understand there's a X-Windows feature that allows this.

> (4) If I send an Email message (that isn't privacy-enhanced in any way)
>     can it be intercepted, and read, by anyone other than the recipient
>     (and super- user on the recipient's system)? 

Anyone that can read files on the systems it gets forwarded through can
read that mail. Anyone that has a hook in a router the mail message gets
routed through can read it, too.

> (5) What (if anything) can be done to protect a Unix system (or individual 
>     users) from these intrusions?

Turn it off.  ;-)

Not speaking for anyone but myself.....        -- Darren
